Plotting the electric field in a reverberation chamber can be quite challenging due to its complex and dynamic nature. The electric field distribution typically exhibits a high degree of randomness and variation within the chamber. However, I can provide you with an example code snippet in MATLAB that demonstrates how you might visualize the electric field distribution using random points:

```matlab
% Define the dimensions and resolution of the reverberation chamber
width = 2;       % Chamber width in meters
height = 2;      % Chamber height in meters
depth = 3;       % Chamber depth in meters
resolution = 0.05;   % Resolution in meters (adjust to your preference)

% Generate random points within the chamber
x = width*rand(1000,1);
y = height*rand(1000,1);
z = depth*rand(1000,1);

% Compute electric field strength at each random point
% You can modify this function based on your specific field distribution model
E = computeElectricField(x, y, z);

% Create a scatter plot of the random points and color code based on electric field strength
scatter3(x, y, z, 50, E, 'filled');
colorbar;

% Set plot properties
axis equal;
xlabel('X');
ylabel('Y');
zlabel('Z');
title('Electric Field Distribution in Reverberation Chamber');

function E = computeElectricField(x, y, z)
